$BR
The correct graph of \(f(x)\)
$ECENTER


By inspection there is a vertical asymptote at \(x=-1\) and an oblique asymptote at \(y=x-1\).
$PAR
\(f'(x) = \frac{x^2+2x-3}{(x+1)^2}\).  From this we can find that there are critical points at \(x=1,-1,-3\).
$PAR
\(f''(x) = \frac{8}{(x+1)^3}\).  The only critical point is \(x=-1\).
$PAR
Therefore: $BR \(A=-3\), $BR \(B=-1\), $BR \(C=1\).
$PAR
By examining the sign of the first and second derivative in the given intervals we find \(f(x)\):
$BR
(\(-\infty,A\)): Increasing and concave down: therefore best represented by graph "4".
$BR  $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE (\(A,B\)): Decreasing and concave down: therefore best represented by graph "3".
$BR $SPACE $SPACE  $SPACE (\(B,C\)): Decreasing and concave up: therefore best represented by graph "2".
$BR $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE (\(C,\infty \)): Increasing and concave up: therefore best represented by graph "1".

